## üéØ Flagship Project: p53-Chromatin Competition

{{< figure src="/images/research/technical-platform.png" alt="Integrated Platform" caption="Multi-scale experimental system combining TIRF microscopy with nano/microfluidics" >}}

### The Central Question

**How does the tumor suppressor p53 access DNA binding sites when chromatin is compacted by histones?**

This competition determines whether p53 can activate its target genes to prevent cancer. Understanding the physical mechanisms is crucial for developing drugs that enhance p53 function.

### Why Current Methods Fall Short

| Limitation | Impact | Our Solution |
|------------|---------|-------------|
| **Bulk biochemistry** | Averages over millions of molecules | Single-molecule resolution |
| **Dilute conditions** | 10-100√ó less crowded than cells | Tunable crowding (0-300 mg/mL) |
| **No spatial control** | Cannot separate crowding vs. confinement effects | Graduated nanochannels (50 nm - 2 ¬µm) |
| **Static endpoints** | Misses dynamic competition | Real-time kinetics tracking |

### Research Strategy

**Stage 1-2: From Components to Competition** (Years 1-3)
- Characterize individual protein-DNA interactions under varying crowding
- Measure p53-histone competition on native genomic sequences
- Quantify how crowding and confinement shift binding equilibrium

**Stage 3: Therapeutic Applications** (Years 4-6)
- Screen compounds that modulate chromatin accessibility
- Identify molecules enhancing p53 binding to target genes
- Develop predictive framework for drug efficacy across cancer types

